As Neil wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/22/2004 at 05:26:20 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>Hi,
>the question is :
>
>suppose that x is an integer such that x+3 divides x^2 + 5x + 5
>find all solutions

There may be a mistake somewhere in the question, but there are no 
values of x for which x+3 divides x^2 + 5x + 5.


>
>[Difficulty]
>I have a method for doing it, but I would like to know if there is 
>another method
>
>[Thoughts]
>since x+3 divides the quadratic, we can say
>
>   x+3.k =x^2 + 5x + 5, where k is an integer
>
>factorising gives :  x+3.k = (x+3)(x+2)-1
>
>so :    (x+3)(x+2-k)=1
>and since x and k are integers we can find all solutions
>
>but is there another way of doing the problem, because for most 
>quadratics we are unable to factorise the RHS completely or 
factorise 
>with a remainder 1 
>
>e.g. if the equation when factorised is x+3.k = (x+3)(x+2)+5 then 
>there is not much you can do about it


